        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <div type="transcription">
<p rend="left">her a little 〈    〉 —</p>
<p>Goodbye my dear Charley I hope we shall hear again soon our best love to dear Emma &amp; Eliz<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</p>
<p>ever y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> affecte. | S E D.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated on the basis of CD’s notes on the verso (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD used the back of this fragment to make the following note: ‘Athenæum /48/ p. 839. Brit. Assoc E. Forbes on genera being continuous in time—<hi rend="doubleUnderline">good</hi>—fact.’ He then pinned this to another note: ‘Athenæum. /48/ p. 247. Lecture by Forbes at Royal Institution on genera being continuous in space &amp; time, ie normally so.— Good for me—&amp; true.— Look at this again—’. The references are to <hi rend="italic">Athenæum</hi>, no. 1086, 19 August 1848, p. 839; and no. 1062, 4 March 1848, p. 247.</note>
        </div>        
            
